headline: US press freedom under scrutiny after arrest of two journalists during Minneapolis protests
subhead: The arrests of Don Lemon, on Thursday evening in Los Angeles, who was released the following day, and reporter Georgia Fort marked another milestone in the American government's political use of the justice system.

headline: US envoy reports 'constructive' Ukraine talks with Russia

Over 300 people thought missing in the Mediterranean as shipwrecks continue amid lack of transparency
subhead: In mid-January, eight vessels that had departed Tunisia were reported in distress. As many as 380 people were on board these boats, according to one radio station. All are now considered missing.

headline: Syria's government reaches agreement with Kurds of Rojava
subhead: A ceasefire has been established after three weeks of fighting. The Kurds have secured major gains in local autonomy and national rights, while the Syrian president claims to have restored national unity.

headline: Catherine O'Hara, iconic comedy figure, dies age 71
subhead: Known for her roles in 'Beetlejuice' and 'Home Alone' on the big screen, and more recently in the series 'Schitt's Creek,' the Canadian-American actress died on Friday, January 30, in Los Angeles following an illness.

headline: An AI clone and a publicly traded company: The irresistible rise of TikToker Khaby Lame
subhead: The Senegalese-Italian influencer has sold his company for nearly $1 billion in a deal that includes the creation of a digital twin powered by artificial intelligence.

Yuri Dmitriev, the Russian historian imprisoned for denouncing Kremlin attempts to rewrite history
subhead: Detained in a penal colony in Mordovia, the 70-year-old historian, who specializes in the Stalin regime's crimes, is one of Russia's oldest political prisoners. His crime? Refusing to accept historical falsifications that the Kremlin aims to impose on public opinion.

headline: 'The only thing left to do is leave': Cuba pushed to the brink
subhead: 'Cuba, an island adrift' (2/3). Since the wave of unrest that swept the country in 2021, more than two million Cubans have fled. Those who remain on the island scrape by with varying degrees of success, as the exorbitant price of basic goods has become a source of inequality between those with nothing and those with access to foreign currency.

headline: 'Facing Trump, Europe, Canada and Latin America have to navigate between misalignment, non-alignment and avoidance'
subhead: The sweeping powers that the US president has granted himself through his Board of Peace serve only to discourage even the best intentions, observes Le Monde's columnist Gilles Paris.
